To prove the `map_eq` field, we use the fact that `X` is Bernoulli distributed to transfer the probability measure to `Ber(u, p)`. We then express `Ber(u, p)` as the image of the infinite product measure under the equivalence `Set ι ≃ (ι → Prop)`. The random variables `fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω` and `fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω` correspond to the projections onto the $i$-th and $j$-th coordinates of this product measure. Since the components of the product measure at $i$ and $j$ are identical (as both $i, j \in u$), the marginal distributions are equal.

```lean
variable (X u p P) in
/-- A random variable `X : Ω → Set ι` is `p`-bernoulli on a set `u : Set ι` if its distribution is
the product over `u` of `p`-bernoulli random variables. -/
abbrev IsBernoulliOn : Prop := HasLaw X Ber(u, p) P

lemma isBernoulliOn_congr (hXY : X =ᵐ[P] Y) : IsBernoulliOn X u p P ↔ IsBernoulliOn Y u p P :=
  hasLaw_congr hXY

lemma IsBernoulliOn.identDistrib_mem (hX : IsBernoulliOn X u p P) (hi : i ∈ u) (hj : j ∈ u) :
    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ i ∈ X ω) (fun ω ↦ j ∈ X ω) P P where
  aemeasurable_fst := by fun_prop
  aemeasurable_snd := by fun_prop
  map_eq := by
    rw [← map_map (by fun_prop) hX.measurable, ← map_map (by fun_prop) hX.measurable, hX.map_eq,
      bernoulliOn_eq_map, map_map (by fun_prop) MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurable,
      map_map (by fun_prop) MeasurableEquiv.setOf.symm.measurable]
    simp only [Function.comp_def, Set.mem_setOf_eq, map_eval_infinitePi]
    simp [hi, hj]
